fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

x = range(len(df1))
y = np.array(df1['4/13/2016'])
z = np.array(df1['4/20/2016'])
yy = np.array(df1['4/25/2016']) 

april_thirteen = ax.scatter(x, y, color='gray')
april_twenty = ax.scatter(x, z, color='darkblue')
april_twentyfive = ax.scatter(x, yy, color='darkgreen')

ax.axhline(int(y.mean()),color='gray', linestyle='dashed', lw=2)
ax.axhline(int(z.mean()),color='darkblue', linestyle='dashed', lw=2)
ax.axhline(int(yy.mean()),color='darkgreen', linestyle='dashed', lw=2)

ax.set_xlabel('(each dot represents a fellow)', fontsize=16)
ax.set_ylabel('# of Connections', fontsize=16)
ax.tick_params(labelsize=12)
ax.set_title('Total # of Connections per Fellow', fontsize=20)
ax.tick_params(labelbottom='off')

ax.annotate('Average on 4/13/15= \n {} connections'.format(int(y.mean())), xy=(135,7.5), color='gray', fontsize=14)
ax.annotate('Average on 4/20/15= \n {} connections'.format(int(z.mean())), xy=(135,11.5),color='darkblue', fontsize=14)
ax.annotate('Average on 4/25/15= \n {} connections'.format(int(yy.mean())),xy=(2, 16.0),color='darkgreen',fontsize=14)
ax.annotate('Max = {} Connections'.format(int(z.max())), xy=(105,35.7),color='black', fontsize=16)
ax.annotate('$\}$',xy=(28, 1), fontsize=50, color='red')
ax.annotate('Less than five: let\'s giddy up!', xy=(38,1.8), color='red', fontsize=18)

ax.set_xlim([-20,len(x)+10])
ax.set_ylim([0,38])

leg = plt.legend([april_twentyfive, april_twenty, april_thirteen], ["As of 4/25/16","As of 4/20/16", "As of 4/13/16"],
                 framealpha=0, bbox_to_anchor=(0.36,.9), fontsize=16)

for text in leg.get_texts():
    if 'As of 4/25/16' in str(text):
        text.set_color("darkgreen")
    if 'As of 4/20/16' in str(text):
        text.set_color("darkblue")

# Create the general plot
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(35,15), tight_layout=True)

# Set the bar width
bar_width = 1

# Position of the left bar-boundaries
bar_1 = [i+1 for i in range(len(df))]

# Position of the x-axis ticks (center of the bars as bar labels)
tick_pos = [i+(bar_width/2) for i in bar_1]

# Create a bar plot in position bar_1
pending = ax1.bar(bar_1, df['Site Visits Pending 4/27'], 
                  width = bar_width, label = 'Pending Onsite Interviews',
                  bottom = df['Site Visits Completed 4/27'],
                  alpha=0.5, color = 'gray')

# Create a bar plot in position bar_1
completed = ax1.bar(bar_1,
        df['Site Visits Completed 4/27'],
        width = bar_width,
        label = 'Completed Onsite Interviews',
        alpha=0.5,
        color = 'darkblue')

# Set the x ticks with names
plt.xticks(tick_pos, np.array(names), fontsize = 14, rotation='vertical')

# Set the label and legends
ax1.set_ylabel("Total # of Onsite Interviews",fontsize=46)
ax1.yaxis.labelpad = 40
ax1.set_xlabel("Fellows",fontsize=46).set_position((0.5,0.8))
ax1.xaxis.labelpad = 40
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', which='major', labelsize=28, pad=20)

# Set axis limits
ax1.set_ylim([0,7])

# Customize Margins
plot_margin = 0.4
x0, x1, y0, y1 = plt.axis()
plt.axis((x0, x1, y0, y1 + plot_margin))

# Set legend
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(0.32,.91), fontsize=40)

# Set Title
ax1.set_title('Onsite Interviews per Fellow as of 4/27/16', fontsize = 60, y = 1.03)

# Annotations
ax1.annotate('# of Fellows with Zero Onsites: {}'.format((df['Total Site Visits'] == 0).sum()),xy=(26,1.35),fontsize=34)

fig.savefig('fig.jpg', dpi=150);

Onsite Interviews (Horizontal Bar Chart - easier to read)¶

In [20]:
# Prepare data frame
df2 = df[['Name', 'Site Visits Pending 4/27', 'Site Visits Completed 4/27']]

# Rename columns
df2.rename(columns={'Site Visits Pending 4/27':'Pending'}, inplace=True)
df2.rename(columns={'Site Visits Completed 4/27':'Completed'}, inplace=True)

# Set names to be the index rather than numbers
df2.set_index(df['Name'], drop=True, inplace=True)

# Calculate summary statistics
zero_c = float((df['Total Site Visits'] == 0).sum())
zero_p = str(int(zero_c))+"   ("+str(int(zero_c / float(len(df))*100))+"%)"

one_c = float((df['Total Site Visits'] == 1).sum())
one_p = str(int(one_c))+"   ("+str(int(one_c / float(len(df))*100))+"%)"

more_c = float((df['Total Site Visits'] > 1).sum())
more_p = str(int(more_c))+"   ("+str(int(more_c / float(len(df))*100))+"%)"
In [21]:
# Plot horizontal stacked bar chart
ax = df2.plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, figsize=(20,40), legend=False, alpha=0.8)

ax.tick_params(axis='y', which='major', labelsize=13)

# Customize legend

# Annotations
